03:45.086 --> 03:47.054
Weaver:
[ Speaking indistinctly ]

03:47.088 --> 03:49.556
Give me that damn gun!

03:49.624 --> 03:51.825
[ Panting ]

03:51.859 --> 03:52.960
Get down here.

03:52.994 --> 03:55.228
[ Sighs ]

03:55.296 --> 03:58.231
They have no reason
to be afraid.

03:58.266 --> 04:02.169
No, but they got plenty
of reasons to hate you.

04:02.236 --> 04:04.671
Case in point.

04:04.706 --> 04:08.141
There's no place for you here --
not anymore.

04:08.176 --> 04:10.677
I'm sorry.

04:13.114 --> 04:15.115
Dr. Kadar had
no definitive proof

04:15.149 --> 04:16.750
she wasn't being
controlled by the Espheni.

04:16.784 --> 04:18.618
How do you know this isn't
some kind of Espheni ploy?

04:18.685 --> 04:20.153
Okay, but why would she
destroy the Beamers?

04:20.188 --> 04:21.654
I don't know.
Doesn't really matter.

04:21.689 --> 04:23.009
There's no guarantee
somebody else

04:23.044 --> 04:24.124
isn't gonna try
to kill her.

04:24.145 --> 04:25.325
You up for that circus?

04:25.360 --> 04:26.960
Okay, I know
what you're feeling.

04:26.995 --> 04:29.229
We're in uncharted territory,
but let me suss this out.

04:29.297 --> 04:31.098
Let me if there's something left
of our daughter over there.

04:31.132 --> 04:33.066
I will keep her away
from the others.

04:33.134 --> 04:34.234
Keep her away from <i>me.</i>

04:44.812 --> 04:46.692
Will you go keep an eye
on Anne and Lexi for me?

04:46.716 --> 04:49.016
Got it. Watch yourself.

04:49.050 --> 04:51.818
Figured you'd show up
sooner or later.

04:51.853 --> 04:53.787
What you just did --
Too far, huh?

04:53.821 --> 04:58.291
Crossed the line?
[ Laughs ]

04:59.694 --> 05:03.930
Somebody needed to do
something!

05:03.965 --> 05:06.099
Too many people have died.

05:06.134 --> 05:09.202
I-I can't stand the thought
of -- of any more --

05:09.237 --> 05:11.004
What is that?
An excuse?

05:11.039 --> 05:12.279
That doesn't give you
the right.

05:12.303 --> 05:13.903
Oh, I think it does.

05:20.715 --> 05:26.887
I can't stop
seeing faces, Mason.

05:30.525 --> 05:34.628
All the dead and buried --

05:34.662 --> 05:37.898
I can't stop
seeing their faces.

05:37.932 --> 05:39.666
Well, there's
a price you pay

05:39.700 --> 05:41.968
for caring about somebody
other than yourself.

05:42.036 --> 05:45.205
2nd Mass?
[ Chuckles ]

05:45.239 --> 05:47.174
[ Sniffs ]
That's funny.

05:48.810 --> 05:50.644
Sara used to tell me

05:50.678 --> 05:52.238
that I actually cared
about your people.

05:52.262 --> 05:54.181
Your people --
not just my people.

05:54.215 --> 05:56.683
Yours as much
as anybody else's.

05:56.717 --> 05:59.219
[ Sniffles ]

05:59.253 --> 06:03.690
I guess you are --

06:03.724 --> 06:06.259
<i>were</i> -- my people.

06:06.294 --> 06:09.830
Know what your problem is,
Mason?

06:09.864 --> 06:13.834
You can't see the forest
through the trees, man --

06:13.868 --> 06:16.269
not when it comes
to family.

06:16.304 --> 06:22.075
We both know that your mouth
masks a lot of damage.

06:22.110 --> 06:24.270
But what you did today,
that was leaping over the line.

06:24.305 --> 06:25.805
I'm not gonna let that
happen again.

06:25.839 --> 06:29.182
My family. My problem.

06:29.217 --> 06:31.852
You stay the hell
out of it.

06:38.192 --> 06:40.026
What's she doing here,
Dad?

06:40.061 --> 06:41.828
She's had a change
of heart.

06:41.863 --> 06:44.131
You believe her?
I don't know.

06:44.198 --> 06:46.318
But you're gonna let her come
back after what she did?

06:46.342 --> 06:47.342
For the time being.

06:47.365 --> 06:49.166
But what if she's all messed up
like Mira was?

06:49.167 --> 06:51.847
Then we'll deal with her the way
that we would deal with any threat.

06:51.871 --> 06:55.008
Look...The launch got scrapped
when she showed up.

06:55.042 --> 06:58.078
Back on now.
We leave in an hour.

07:02.683 --> 07:05.619
Cochise: There are too many unknown
variables on this mission.

07:05.653 --> 07:08.021
Yeah, well,
that's why I stayed up late

07:08.055 --> 07:10.524
and reread "Space Flight
for Dummies" last night.

07:10.558 --> 07:11.958
[ Sighs ]

07:11.993 --> 07:14.794
Look, Cochise, it's --
it's a long shot.

07:14.829 --> 07:16.263
We knew that going in.

07:16.297 --> 07:19.866
But this is where the Espheni's
advanced technology

07:19.901 --> 07:21.101
works in our favor.

07:21.135 --> 07:22.615
I mean, this ship is
light-years ahead

07:22.639 --> 07:24.070
of anything that we've got,

07:24.105 --> 07:28.175
with the automated life support
and the homing signal.

07:28.242 --> 07:31.578
All I really need to do
is fly straight up.

07:31.612 --> 07:35.615
Right?

07:35.650 --> 07:38.685
So, why do you seem
so agitated?

07:40.688 --> 07:42.848
I would be more comfortable
if I were accompanying you.

07:42.872 --> 07:44.157
Well, so would I.

07:44.192 --> 07:46.893
But this ship is allergic
to Volm technology.

07:46.928 --> 07:49.696
If the Espheni hadn't built their
Beamers to literally reject you,

07:49.730 --> 07:51.998
you'd be warming up the copilot
seat as we speak.

07:52.033 --> 07:53.533
There is another option.
What?

07:53.568 --> 07:55.535
I have been trying to send
messages to my father

07:55.570 --> 07:57.103
on our subspace communicator.
Yeah.

07:57.138 --> 07:59.673
As yet,
he has not answered,

07:59.707 --> 08:01.942
but please hold the launch
long enough for him to do so.

08:01.976 --> 08:04.077
[ Sighs ] If the greater Volm
are within range,

08:04.111 --> 08:05.812
they could offer
immeasurable support.

08:05.880 --> 08:07.400
No, we can't afford
to hold the launch.

08:07.424 --> 08:08.648
We have no way of knowing

08:08.683 --> 08:10.550
if the power core
is guarded or not.

08:10.585 --> 08:12.552
If my father receives
these messages,

08:12.587 --> 08:14.688
and if he chooses to respond,
he could run interference.

08:14.722 --> 08:16.402
What do you mean,
<i>if</i> he chooses to respond?

08:16.426 --> 08:17.791
Why wouldn't he choose
to respond?

08:17.825 --> 08:20.060
[ Footsteps ]

08:20.094 --> 08:24.097
Excuse me. Is there something
you're not telling me?

08:24.165 --> 08:28.201
My father and I did not part
well, Tom Mason.

08:28.236 --> 08:30.870
He insisted that I leave
with him,

08:30.938 --> 08:33.006
that Earth was
a lost cause.

08:33.039 --> 08:36.109
[ Sighs ]
I-I refused.

08:36.143 --> 08:38.645
I told him I would find
the power core

08:38.679 --> 08:40.714
and I would destroy it
on my own.

08:40.748 --> 08:44.484
Are you telling that you
and your team and Shaq --

08:44.518 --> 08:47.854
you guys
are all we've got?

08:51.292 --> 08:53.412
Well, I'm sorry, but unless you
can give us some proof

08:53.436 --> 08:54.728
that your dad's
gonna help us,

08:54.762 --> 08:56.242
I think we need to proceed
as planned.

08:58.633 --> 09:00.200
You're worried
about the variables?

09:00.234 --> 09:02.035
Help me strap down
the bombs.

09:06.140 --> 09:09.209
Lexi, take a seat
on the bed.

09:09.243 --> 09:11.745
I need a couple minutes alone
with her.

09:11.779 --> 09:13.713
Pope took a cheap shot
at her,

09:13.748 --> 09:15.188
there's a lot of people
with grudges,

09:15.223 --> 09:16.903
and I'm not gonna let
anything happen to...

09:16.927 --> 09:18.218
either one of you.

09:18.286 --> 09:19.953
Okay.

09:22.189 --> 09:23.523
[ Sighs ]

09:23.591 --> 09:27.127
Thank you so much, Mom.
I --

09:27.161 --> 09:28.721
Stop playing games.
I'm not in the mood.

09:28.729 --> 09:31.064
Games?
I-I don't understand.

09:31.098 --> 09:33.066
Appealing
to my maternal instinct

09:33.100 --> 09:34.968
doesn't change the fact
that I can't trust you.

09:35.002 --> 09:36.603
You could be
under Espheni control.

09:36.637 --> 09:40.640
They can't control me.
That's why they're afraid of me.

09:40.675 --> 09:42.809
When you killed Lourdes,
your friend,

09:42.843 --> 09:44.163
they weren't
controlling you then?

09:44.187 --> 09:45.712
I was confused.

09:45.746 --> 09:50.550
I -- I thought it was sparing
her from a painful death.

09:50.618 --> 09:52.752
Now I understand how twisted
that logic was,

09:52.820 --> 09:53.987
but in that moment, I...

09:54.021 --> 09:57.857
[ Sighs ]
I'm sorry.

09:57.892 --> 10:00.894
No, I wasn't
under their control.

10:01.212 --> 10:02.879
It was my own decision.

10:08.920 --> 10:10.754
[ Sighs ]
Lexi.

10:10.788 --> 10:12.422
I made a choice

10:12.490 --> 10:14.424
between my human family
and my Espheni family.

10:14.492 --> 10:17.127
Don't call those monsters
family.

10:17.161 --> 10:19.529
I wanted peace so badly
that I believed their lies.

10:19.597 --> 10:22.299
And I believed yours!

10:22.367 --> 10:23.500
I searched for you, Lexi.

10:23.534 --> 10:25.302
When I lost you,

10:25.336 --> 10:27.416
I would've gone to the ends
of the earth to find you,

10:27.440 --> 10:31.174
to find a way for us
to be together -- a family.

10:31.209 --> 10:33.510
But you --
you betrayed all of that!

10:33.544 --> 10:38.148
Now I know
that's never gonna happen --

10:38.182 --> 10:40.450
not now,
not after what you did.

10:40.485 --> 10:45.255
I know how badly
I violated your trust.

10:45.289 --> 10:50.060
So please, please,
let me make it up to you.

10:50.128 --> 10:51.995
I'm your best chance

10:52.030 --> 10:54.230
if you want to make it to
the power core and destroy it.

10:54.254 --> 10:57.100
How do you know
about that?

10:57.135 --> 10:59.503
When I was
with the Espheni,

10:59.537 --> 11:01.838
I-I learned how to control
my abilities.

11:01.873 --> 11:05.409
I -- I --
it's hard to explain.

11:05.443 --> 11:07.044
You better try.

11:07.078 --> 11:11.381
It's like I can see energy,

11:11.416 --> 11:13.216
manipulate it, all of it --

11:13.251 --> 11:17.954
gravity, radio waves,
electrical charges.

11:17.989 --> 11:20.857
And if I'm close enough, I can
access the Beamer systems.

11:20.892 --> 11:22.325
I can control them.

11:26.431 --> 11:28.398
Tom: <i>No, we can't afford</i>
<i>to hold the launch.</i>

11:28.433 --> 11:30.400
Cochise: <i>We have</i>
<i>no way of knowing</i>

11:30.435 --> 11:32.069
<i>if the power core</i>
<i>is guarded or not.</i>

11:32.103 --> 11:34.463
I can hear the conversation
on the ship -- the Volm and dad.

11:34.487 --> 11:36.373
They're preparing a bomb
you've built.

11:36.407 --> 11:39.509
Stop that! Don't do that!

11:39.544 --> 11:42.145
Is that why you're here?
No.

11:42.180 --> 11:43.980
Did the Espheni send you
to spy on us?

11:44.048 --> 11:45.382
No. No, no! I promise.

11:45.416 --> 11:47.884
Please.
I'm telling the truth.

11:47.919 --> 11:50.220
I rejected my Espheni father.
I want to help.

11:50.288 --> 11:52.556
The bomb you built
may be powerful enough

11:52.590 --> 11:55.225
to make it to the power core
and destroy it,

11:55.259 --> 11:57.094
but you'd have
to get it there first.

11:57.128 --> 11:59.863
You may have managed to get
that Beamer airborne,

11:59.897 --> 12:01.898
but to fly it
to the moon and back?

12:01.966 --> 12:05.869
If you attempt this without
my help, you'll die trying.

12:05.903 --> 12:07.984
Anne, if she knows about
the Beamer, then we don't --

12:08.008 --> 12:09.272
Dan, please! Please.

12:09.273 --> 12:12.275
I knew I had to come back.
This is the reason.

12:12.310 --> 12:14.845
I can fly the Beamer,
defend it if it's attacked.

12:14.879 --> 12:16.980
I should be the one
going on this mission.

12:17.014 --> 12:18.515
Please, please,
don't sacrifice

12:18.549 --> 12:20.183
any more
than you already have.

12:20.251 --> 12:21.251
No.

12:23.087 --> 12:27.124
No, Lexi.

12:27.191 --> 12:29.526
You have made
your choices,

12:29.594 --> 12:32.863
and there's no coming back
from them.

12:32.897 --> 12:35.298
[ Voice breaking ]
And I'm your mother,

12:35.333 --> 12:37.534
and I will always love you,

12:37.568 --> 12:41.304
and I pray every day that you
find your place in this world.

12:41.339 --> 12:43.140
[ Sniffles ]

12:43.174 --> 12:45.542
But it isn't here --

12:45.576 --> 12:49.312
not with us, not now.

12:54.118 --> 12:56.987
[ Sniffles ]
Tom was right.

13:00.024 --> 13:01.224
You need to leave.

13:01.259 --> 13:04.761
Weaver:
Anne, we need to talk now.

13:04.796 --> 13:06.763
Dan, this isn't the time.
Now <i>is</i> the time.

13:06.798 --> 13:08.131
[ Sighs ]

13:08.166 --> 13:10.100
I think you and Tom are
making a huge mistake.

13:10.168 --> 13:11.168
About what?

13:11.169 --> 13:12.769
About your daughter.

13:27.037 --> 13:29.038
Tom.

13:29.073 --> 13:31.007
Where's Lexi?

13:31.041 --> 13:33.170
Anthony's keeping an eye on her
so she can stay alive

13:33.171 --> 13:35.011
long enough for us to talk
about the situation.

13:35.035 --> 13:36.934
What's the situation?
Just hear him out.

13:36.935 --> 13:38.601
Lexi has made an offer

13:38.669 --> 13:40.629
that I think it'd be
shortsighted not to consider.

13:40.653 --> 13:42.872
What's the offer?

13:42.906 --> 13:44.440
To go on the mission
with you

13:44.508 --> 13:46.576
instead of Ben.
Huh.

13:46.610 --> 13:47.492
You're on board with that?

13:47.516 --> 13:49.396
I think it's something
we should consider, yeah.

13:49.420 --> 13:51.681
She just took down
those Beamers, Tom.

13:51.715 --> 13:56.386
She just heard you and Cochise
talking inside of ours.

13:56.420 --> 13:58.821
She's not Jeanne, okay?

13:58.856 --> 14:01.891
Your daughter held on to her
humanity with every fiber. Ours didn't.

14:01.925 --> 14:04.794
Okay, you're right. She was
a willing participant. She admitted it.

14:04.828 --> 14:07.964
But does that change the fact
that she is our best chance --

14:07.998 --> 14:10.033
maybe our only chance?

14:10.100 --> 14:12.302
I understand
that emotions are raw.

14:12.336 --> 14:14.971
I understand that.
But this is war.

14:15.039 --> 14:16.572
We can't think
with our hearts.

14:16.607 --> 14:18.641
We got to think
with our heads.

14:18.709 --> 14:21.544
Remember when the allies had to team up
with Stalin in order to defeat Hitler?

14:21.612 --> 14:23.012
They knew that joining forces,

14:23.080 --> 14:25.348
even with you joining forces
with a monster, would be --

14:25.382 --> 14:27.102
Yeah, to win the war,
but we don't need her.

14:27.126 --> 14:28.484
We've already done
our homework.

14:28.552 --> 14:29.919
Unless the power core
is heavily guarded

14:29.953 --> 14:31.688
or we encounter
something else unexpected.

14:31.722 --> 14:32.889
I mean, having someone
that can operate the machinery

14:32.956 --> 14:34.586
just might make
the difference.

14:34.587 --> 14:35.137
Yes.

14:35.161 --> 14:37.241
I mean, we can't argue
the fact that Lexi's abilities

14:37.795 --> 14:39.896
give her an edge
that none of us have.

14:39.930 --> 14:42.832
Are you not even willing
to entertain that idea?

14:42.866 --> 14:45.735
Ben and I have been over
every step of this mission.

14:45.769 --> 14:47.637
I've seen him in
pressure situations before.

14:47.671 --> 14:48.738
I know how he'll respond.

14:48.772 --> 14:49.963
Okay, so you're afraid
of her?

14:49.964 --> 14:51.247
I'm afraid of myself
around her.

14:52.876 --> 14:54.836
I'm afraid that I'm not gonna
make the right call.

14:54.860 --> 14:57.313
I-I don't know her.
And none of it matters.

14:57.348 --> 15:00.583
This is our hail Mary.

15:00.617 --> 15:01.718
Throw all that out.

15:01.752 --> 15:04.620
It's simple.
It's just a choice, Tom.

15:04.655 --> 15:06.823
Listen,
maybe you're right.

15:06.857 --> 15:09.025
Maybe I'm...

15:09.059 --> 15:11.561
Letting my emotions
cloud my judgment.

15:11.595 --> 15:13.262
I should make this decision

15:13.297 --> 15:15.064
on a purely tactical,
logical basis.

15:15.099 --> 15:16.099
I-I don't know.

15:20.404 --> 15:21.871
Yeah, when you weigh it
all out,

15:21.939 --> 15:23.573
she's the best person
for it.

15:29.380 --> 15:31.481
All right, Lexi goes.
Ben stays.

15:31.515 --> 15:34.550
[ Sighs ]
Hope to god we're right.

15:42.659 --> 15:45.528
Thank you for giving me
this opportunity.

15:45.562 --> 15:48.464
It's more out of necessity
than choice.

15:48.499 --> 15:50.400
Hey, what's that?

15:50.467 --> 15:52.902
It's bad luck not to christen
a ship on its maiden voyage.

15:52.936 --> 15:55.772
I think we may be a little
past luck, but thank you.

15:57.808 --> 16:00.089
Hey, listen, I don't care how
powerful they say you are --

16:00.113 --> 16:02.247
if you hurt my dad, I'll find
a way to make you pay.

16:04.014 --> 16:06.582
This isn't fair.
We had a lottery. I know.

16:06.617 --> 16:09.719
If it was fair, I'd be teaching
second-period American history right now.

16:09.753 --> 16:10.987
This is the way
it has to be.

16:11.021 --> 16:13.322
Ben, I --

16:13.357 --> 16:14.891
There's nothing
to say, Lexi.

16:14.958 --> 16:17.693
I can think
of a few choice words.

16:17.728 --> 16:20.696
Yeah, I want to thank you
for being the first and last

16:20.731 --> 16:24.867
I ever let tell me
who I'm supposed to be.

16:24.902 --> 16:26.836
You know, it's a real shame
that Lourdes

16:26.870 --> 16:29.405
was the only one among us
who might have been able

16:29.440 --> 16:31.607
to find a place in her heart
to forgive you.

16:34.244 --> 16:36.279
I'll hold you
to your word.

16:36.346 --> 16:39.282
I want you both to come back
in one piece.

16:43.887 --> 16:45.521
I'll try my best.

16:45.556 --> 16:49.559
No trying, kid.
Get it done.

16:59.603 --> 17:00.603
Come here a second.

17:00.637 --> 17:03.339
[ Beamer whirring ]

17:03.407 --> 17:07.276
I, uh...got this serum
from the Volm.

17:07.310 --> 17:09.811
They carry it on them in case
they get captured by the Espheni.

17:09.847 --> 17:11.881
It's a fast-acting poison.

17:11.915 --> 17:14.835
Now, if that's strong enough to take
down a Volm before it can regenerate,

17:14.858 --> 17:17.887
might be able to kill
a hybrid.

17:17.921 --> 17:22.657
Just think of it
as an insurance policy.

17:22.693 --> 17:24.060
Let's hope I won't need it.
Mm.

17:40.410 --> 17:42.378
[ Whirring ]

18:16.346 --> 18:18.381
Oh, godspeed.

18:22.477 --> 18:24.412
[ Groans ]

18:24.446 --> 18:26.347
I can't breathe!

18:26.415 --> 18:29.016
We should clear
the atmosphere

18:29.051 --> 18:31.185
in a few...moments.

18:40.429 --> 18:42.930
[ Both gasping ]

18:42.965 --> 18:44.231
[ Coughs ]

18:46.034 --> 18:49.470
I've adjusted
the linear-acceleration burn.

18:49.504 --> 18:52.974
We should mimic
the earth's gravity.

18:53.008 --> 18:54.442
If we're out
of the atmosphere,

18:54.476 --> 18:56.644
we should be able to detect
the homing beacon.

18:56.678 --> 19:00.081
I've found the signal
and engaged autopilot.

19:00.115 --> 19:03.150
Nothing more to do now
but wait.

19:03.185 --> 19:05.586
[ Sighs ]

19:05.620 --> 19:10.524
You still don't trust me,
do you?

19:10.559 --> 19:13.127
Why don't you ask me
that question

19:13.161 --> 19:15.262
when we're
on the way home?

19:15.297 --> 19:16.964
How long
until we get there?

19:17.032 --> 19:18.599
One moment.

19:28.977 --> 19:31.879
This map will allow us to view
the ship's course

19:31.913 --> 19:34.482
in relation to the nearest
celestial bodies.

19:36.318 --> 19:37.618
Is something wrong?

19:37.686 --> 19:39.453
No.

19:39.521 --> 19:41.255
That thing you're doing
with your hair --

19:41.289 --> 19:42.656
your mother
does that sometimes.

19:44.393 --> 19:46.560
Um, let's go over
the checklist again.

19:46.595 --> 19:48.562
The homing beacon
is engaged.

19:48.597 --> 19:51.499
When we reach our destination,
I'll switch it off

19:51.533 --> 19:54.235
and let the core's landing
protocol draw us in.

19:54.269 --> 19:57.104
And then we drop the bomb,
blow up the power core,

19:57.139 --> 19:58.539
and you fly this ship home
manually.

19:58.563 --> 19:59.314
Yeah.

19:59.337 --> 20:01.275
And it's important
that we conserve power

20:01.276 --> 20:04.145
because the return trip's
on a battery charge?

20:04.212 --> 20:09.050
Half charge on the battery
should be enough to get us home.

20:09.084 --> 20:11.952
Are we forgetting
anything?

20:11.987 --> 20:14.121
It's nothing --

20:14.156 --> 20:17.558
I mean, nothing to do with
the ship, anyway. It's just...

20:17.592 --> 20:19.627
This is the longest conversation
we've ever had.

20:19.661 --> 20:22.930
It's not really the time or the place
to get to know each other.

20:22.964 --> 20:26.934
We're on a mission.
I think we should stick to it.

20:26.968 --> 20:28.569
Right.

20:28.603 --> 20:31.672
It's getting colder in here.
Why is that?

20:31.706 --> 20:34.241
Let me check life support.

20:39.014 --> 20:41.115
The outer hull --

20:41.149 --> 20:43.451
there appears to be
a hairline fracture.

20:43.518 --> 20:45.419
Uh, we did
some minor repairs.

20:45.454 --> 20:47.388
Takeoff may have worsened
the tear.

20:47.422 --> 20:48.942
Life support is making up
for the leak,

20:48.966 --> 20:50.458
but causing us
to drain energy

20:50.492 --> 20:52.326
at a much faster rate
than we should.

20:52.360 --> 20:54.228
Can we fix it?
From outside of the ship,

20:54.296 --> 20:56.664
with the right tools,
but here, now -- no.

20:56.698 --> 20:58.933
No, I mean,
we could return home...

20:58.967 --> 21:01.469
No. No, come on.
...Make repairs, and try again.

21:01.503 --> 21:04.071
Come on! There's got to be
some other way around this!

21:04.106 --> 21:05.473
[ Sighs ]

21:05.507 --> 21:06.707
If we can't get outside
and repair the damage,

21:06.741 --> 21:08.109
then there's got to be
another way

21:08.176 --> 21:10.244
to take the strain off
of the life support.

21:10.278 --> 21:12.379
Unless we lower it
to a minimum,

21:12.414 --> 21:14.281
this will be a one-way trip
to the moon.

21:18.353 --> 21:21.255
And even if we turn
the ship around,

21:21.289 --> 21:22.523
there's no guarantee

21:22.557 --> 21:24.658
that we could repair
the breach in the hull.

21:24.693 --> 21:26.427
There's got to be
another way.

21:26.495 --> 21:28.195
There is one other option,

21:28.230 --> 21:31.632
a way to insulate us from
the cold, um, organically.

21:31.666 --> 21:34.702
Well, good.
That sounds good.

21:34.736 --> 21:36.971
Wait, you mean like
the thing in Chinatown?

21:37.005 --> 21:38.205
A cocoon, yes.
No, no.

21:38.240 --> 21:40.241
This will be different
than before.

21:40.275 --> 21:42.543
Cocoons are used by the Espheni
for stasis,

21:42.577 --> 21:45.713
protection against the elements
during long journeys.

21:45.747 --> 21:48.516
You mean like a cocoon
to protect us from the cold?

21:48.583 --> 21:50.251
And lack of oxygen.

21:50.285 --> 21:52.586
I'll be able to hear
the automated landing protocol

21:52.621 --> 21:55.689
from inside of the cocoon as
we approach our destination.

21:55.724 --> 21:58.125
At that point,
I'll restart life support

21:58.160 --> 22:01.061
and let landing protocol
take over.

22:01.096 --> 22:03.931
It's our only chance
of survival.

22:03.965 --> 22:05.666
[ Shivering ]

22:14.543 --> 22:18.145
The cold -- it --
it doesn't bother you?

22:18.180 --> 22:22.349
I can regulate my body temperature,
but only to a point.

22:22.384 --> 22:24.618
I'll have to cocoon myself,
too -- and soon.

22:36.331 --> 22:40.000
What is that?
Protein. Amino acids.

22:40.035 --> 22:44.171
Honestly, it would take
too long to explain.

22:52.647 --> 22:54.415
Hold still.

23:07.963 --> 23:11.565
No, wait, wait.
How am I gonna breathe?

23:11.600 --> 23:14.301
The substance I'm secreting
is oxygen-rich.

23:14.336 --> 23:16.637
It'll enter your lungs
and nourish you.

23:16.671 --> 23:18.305
But you have to let it in.

23:20.008 --> 23:22.443
It'll be like no time
at all has passed.

23:22.510 --> 23:25.679
When we wake up,
we'll simply be there.

23:25.714 --> 23:27.615
Okay.

23:27.649 --> 23:31.919
Now, just breathe deeply.

23:33.388 --> 23:36.957
That's what you said
to Lourdes right before...

23:36.992 --> 23:40.527
Did I? How strange.

23:40.595 --> 23:44.365
Wait.
[ Gagging ]

23:46.501 --> 23:48.502
Sweet dreams, father.

23:52.461 --> 23:55.022
Anne:
Tom! Can you hear me?! Tom!

23:55.624 --> 23:57.926
We're gonna get you
out of there!

23:57.960 --> 24:00.195
Hey, Dad! Dad!

24:00.262 --> 24:02.063
Stay with us! You okay?
Yeah.

24:02.097 --> 24:04.732
Hang in there. Stay with us.
You all right?

24:04.767 --> 24:06.901
[ Both grunting ]

24:06.936 --> 24:09.571
Here. Oh.
Oh, oh.

24:09.605 --> 24:11.706
There you go.
Take it easy. Yeah.

24:13.709 --> 24:15.910
[ Coughing ]

24:15.978 --> 24:17.512
Oh, god. Are you okay?

24:17.546 --> 24:20.782
Where am I?
What happened?

24:20.816 --> 24:22.851
You made it back.
You're back.

24:22.918 --> 24:25.420
What do you mean, back?

24:25.487 --> 24:28.122
What -- what --
what happened to your arm?

24:28.157 --> 24:29.891
[ Sighs ] I'm fine.
So is Lexi.

24:29.925 --> 24:32.493
W-where's Lexi?
What happened?

24:32.528 --> 24:33.628
She wanted to be here
when you woke up,

24:33.696 --> 24:35.063
but she's been
through so much.

24:35.097 --> 24:36.097
Hey, what -- are you repairing
the breach to the hull?

24:36.131 --> 24:37.765
How much time did we lose?!

24:37.800 --> 24:39.067
It's over! Lexi did it.

24:39.101 --> 24:41.035
Did what?!
I don't understand!

24:41.070 --> 24:43.104
Hey, hey, hey, hey, whoa.
The mission.

24:43.138 --> 24:44.472
All right? It's over.

24:44.506 --> 24:46.007
Yeah. It's over.
All right?

24:46.041 --> 24:47.775
Come here.
We'll show you.

24:49.778 --> 24:51.512
Just take it easy.

24:51.547 --> 24:53.681
[ Indistinct conversations ]

24:53.716 --> 24:54.949
Anne:
A day after you left,

24:54.984 --> 24:56.818
there was a massive explosion
on the Moon.

24:56.852 --> 24:58.052
Tom: Power core?

24:58.087 --> 24:59.153
That crater
is where it used to be.

24:59.188 --> 25:00.221
Lexi detonated the bomb.

25:00.256 --> 25:01.956
And just in the nick
of time.

25:02.024 --> 25:04.184
That scorched Overlord sent in
a whole group of troops.

25:04.208 --> 25:06.494
There was a whole wave of
skitters trying to soften us up.

25:06.528 --> 25:08.529
We were about out of ammo,
had nowhere to run to.

25:08.564 --> 25:09.898
And a skitter took me down,

25:09.932 --> 25:11.652
but Hal fought it off,
stopped the bleeding.

25:11.676 --> 25:13.067
The right place
at the right time.

25:13.102 --> 25:15.383
Well, if Lexi hadn't blown up
the power core when she did,

25:15.407 --> 25:16.537
none of us
would be here.

25:16.572 --> 25:18.673
Once he saw that the power
supply had been cut,

25:18.707 --> 25:20.208
that Espheni
turned tail and ran.

25:20.242 --> 25:22.042
So Lexi never got me out
of the cocoon at all?

25:22.044 --> 25:23.544
No, she did it
on her own.

25:23.612 --> 25:25.172
She docked the Beamer,
she set the bomb,

25:25.239 --> 25:27.319
and flew you back before
the battery charge ran down.

25:27.343 --> 25:28.650
She did it, Tom.
I know, right?

25:28.717 --> 25:30.852
Where's Lexi now?
I want to talk to her.

25:30.920 --> 25:32.954
Come on. Let's go.

25:39.962 --> 25:41.195
What happened to her?

25:41.230 --> 25:42.597
I'll let her tell you.

25:46.168 --> 25:49.604
Lexi. Wake up.

25:55.577 --> 25:58.546
I wanted to be there
when you woke up.

25:58.580 --> 25:59.814
[ Sighs ]

26:02.084 --> 26:05.753
Last thing I remember,
you were putting me in a cocoon.

26:05.821 --> 26:08.623
The life-support strain on the
batteries was worse than I thought.

26:08.657 --> 26:12.493
I couldn't risk waking you,
or we'd never have made it back.

26:12.528 --> 26:15.029
When the bomb exploded,
the power core melted down,

26:15.064 --> 26:18.666
and, well, we were caught
in the radiation blast wave.

26:18.701 --> 26:22.136
You look so different now --
your hair.

26:22.171 --> 26:25.940
Yeah, it's like radiation
therapy attacking cancer cells.

26:25.975 --> 26:28.676
Her Espheni DNA seems to have
been flushed out of her system.

26:28.711 --> 26:32.180
I-I can't hear them
in my mind anymore.

26:32.214 --> 26:35.450
For the first time since I was
a little girl, I...

26:35.484 --> 26:37.618
[ Chuckles ]
I feel normal.

26:39.521 --> 26:40.421
Dad!

26:40.456 --> 26:42.090
[ Laughs ]

26:42.124 --> 26:43.858
Hello.

26:43.892 --> 26:46.961
Ben.
You brought him back in one piece.

26:46.996 --> 26:49.764
It's not enough.
It won't ever be enough.

26:49.798 --> 26:52.533
I'll spend the rest
of my life making up

26:52.568 --> 26:54.802
for what I did to Lourdes,
deserting the 2nd Mass.

26:54.837 --> 26:57.438
No, that doesn't matter.

26:57.473 --> 27:00.174
You're one of us.
You're family.

27:00.209 --> 27:01.776
Where's everybody else?

27:01.810 --> 27:03.878
Where's Weaver?
Where's Maggie?

27:03.946 --> 27:05.513
Well, the colonel's
got everybody mobilized

27:05.547 --> 27:07.467
to take advantage of
the Espheni's loss of power.

27:07.491 --> 27:09.211
Don't worry.
He's gonna want to talk to you.

27:10.619 --> 27:12.053
In a minute.

27:12.087 --> 27:14.722
[ Chuckles ]

27:14.757 --> 27:16.491
In a minute.

27:17.760 --> 27:19.427
Weaver: Got a shortwave
up and running.

27:19.495 --> 27:20.855
Been hearing
from resistance groups

27:20.863 --> 27:22.103
all up and down the East Coast.

27:22.127 --> 27:23.965
Without power from the core,

27:23.999 --> 27:26.501
all the ghetto walls
have fallen.

27:26.535 --> 27:28.002
The Espheni plans for us
have come to a halt.

27:28.070 --> 27:29.437
What about our old friend,
that scorched Overlord?

27:29.471 --> 27:30.871
He's pulling back
to his stronghold.

27:30.895 --> 27:32.473
For the first time,
a fair fight.

27:32.508 --> 27:34.776
Well, how do we know that he's
not just pulling back,

27:34.843 --> 27:37.445
regrouping, and about to launch
a major counteroffensive?

27:37.479 --> 27:40.014
How do we know that
the tide hasn't turned

27:40.049 --> 27:42.817
and that this just may be
a winnable war?

27:42.885 --> 27:45.620
I'm just saying we should
be...cautious.

27:45.654 --> 27:46.821
Let's scope it out,

27:46.855 --> 27:48.823
and if everything is
as it seems...

27:48.857 --> 27:50.758
We press our advantage.

27:53.195 --> 27:55.129
[ Indistinct conversations ]

27:58.467 --> 27:59.734
You're quiet.

27:59.768 --> 28:02.103
I can't believe
I'm actually looking

28:02.137 --> 28:05.006
at the light at the end
of the tunnel.

28:05.040 --> 28:08.176
I've dreamt about this day
a thousand times over.

28:08.210 --> 28:10.778
After everything
we've been through,

28:10.846 --> 28:12.547
we deserve a little joy
in our life.

28:13.949 --> 28:17.085
Lexi,
can I talk to you alone?

28:21.924 --> 28:23.958
Yeah, I just think we need
to clear the air.

28:24.026 --> 28:25.693
I know you're angry at me,
Maggie,

28:25.727 --> 28:27.528
and you have every right
to be.

28:27.563 --> 28:30.631
Maybe I do, but at least
I'm alive and angry

28:30.666 --> 28:32.133
and not a pissed-off corpse.

28:32.167 --> 28:36.504
And I have you to thank
for that, so...

28:36.538 --> 28:39.474
I guess that's
what I'm saying.

28:39.541 --> 28:42.110
Thanks for that.

28:45.681 --> 28:49.150
Where's Pope? It's not like him
to miss a party.

28:49.184 --> 28:52.420
Um, he left right after
the launch of the Beamer.

28:52.454 --> 28:54.088
No one
has seen him since.

28:54.123 --> 28:55.623
He left?

28:55.657 --> 28:57.024
Mm-hmm.

28:57.092 --> 28:59.527
For real?

28:59.561 --> 29:01.496
[ Laughs ]

29:04.766 --> 29:05.933
[ Indistinct shouting ]

29:05.968 --> 29:07.468
What's going on
over there?

29:07.536 --> 29:08.536
Anthony:
We just got word.

29:08.604 --> 29:10.138
Dingaan and Hal's attack

29:10.172 --> 29:12.707
on the scorched Overlord's
stronghold was a success --

29:12.741 --> 29:14.942
a few fighters wounded,
but no casualties.

29:15.010 --> 29:18.179
What do you mean, attack?
I never authorized an attack.

29:18.213 --> 29:20.581
This was just in the planning
stages this afternoon.

29:20.616 --> 29:23.084
Weaver must have given it
the go-ahead.

29:23.118 --> 29:24.218
That doesn't sound like him.
Why would he do that?

29:24.253 --> 29:25.987
Well, you can ask
him yourself.

29:26.021 --> 29:27.522
Time to bring out the good stuff --
what's left of it, anyway.

29:27.556 --> 29:29.357
What is this
about an attack?

29:29.391 --> 29:31.492
We never pulled the trigger on that.
Hal made the call.

29:31.527 --> 29:33.808
He knew that if you knew it
was on, you'd insist on going.

29:33.832 --> 29:34.832
He wasn't wrong, was he?

29:36.098 --> 29:39.066
[ Coughs ] Wipe that look
off your face, Mason.

29:39.134 --> 29:40.668
You've got so used
to losing,

29:40.702 --> 29:42.462
you don't know what it's like
to win anymore.

29:44.006 --> 29:46.674
Listen. I need
your undivided attention.

29:46.708 --> 29:48.176
Yeah?

29:48.210 --> 29:53.214
And just don't say a word.
Just come with me.

30:07.029 --> 30:09.030
[ Chuckles ]

30:10.966 --> 30:13.568
Mm.

30:15.904 --> 30:17.705
Hey, don't you think
that was weird

30:17.739 --> 30:19.574
the way that Weaver
just blew me off?

30:19.608 --> 30:21.075
Well, he was excited.

30:21.109 --> 30:24.011
We all are. Is it so wrong
to want to celebrate?

30:24.046 --> 30:26.514
No. It's not.

30:26.548 --> 30:27.615
Mm.

30:30.252 --> 30:32.019
That stronghold
that Hal attacked today,

30:32.054 --> 30:33.888
that was 30 miles away,
right?

30:33.922 --> 30:35.156
Mm-hmm.

30:35.190 --> 30:38.826
So...

30:38.860 --> 30:40.861
How did they get there
so quickly?

30:40.929 --> 30:42.597
Um, the militia troops

30:42.631 --> 30:45.700
that Dingaan connected with
had transport.

30:45.734 --> 30:47.201
Oh.

30:47.236 --> 30:49.770
That's convenient.

30:49.805 --> 30:54.141
It's perfect.
It's too perfect.

30:54.176 --> 30:55.610
It's too perfect.

30:55.644 --> 30:57.004
It's too perfect,
it's too perfect,

30:57.038 --> 30:58.038
it's perf-- [ Sighs ]

30:58.073 --> 30:59.213
What?

30:59.248 --> 31:01.482
[ Sighs ]

31:01.516 --> 31:04.719
Doesn't add up.

31:04.753 --> 31:07.888
The war is coming
to an end.

31:07.923 --> 31:09.257
For the first time
in I don't know how long,

31:09.291 --> 31:10.891
there is no mission
to be planned,

31:10.926 --> 31:12.226
no lives that need
to be saved,

31:12.261 --> 31:14.629
no command decisions
to be made.

31:14.663 --> 31:16.097
Lexi did it.

31:16.131 --> 31:19.734
Her dream of peace
is finally coming true.

31:19.768 --> 31:21.769
She did it, Tom.

31:21.803 --> 31:23.204
Yeah.

31:23.238 --> 31:27.541
And then I heard
your voice...

31:27.576 --> 31:29.010
When you pulled me out.

31:29.044 --> 31:30.044
Mm-hmm.

31:33.682 --> 31:35.516
<i>If</i> you pulled me out.

31:36.785 --> 31:38.686
What is that
supposed to mean?

31:40.255 --> 31:43.124
This doesn't feel real.

31:43.158 --> 31:44.592
What?

31:44.626 --> 31:45.893
Okay, I'm not real?

31:45.927 --> 31:46.927
I don't feel like I'm --

31:46.962 --> 31:48.496
I mean, I know the feeling.

31:48.563 --> 31:50.203
I feel like I'm here,
but I don't think --

31:50.227 --> 31:51.532
I-I don't feel
like I'm here.

31:51.566 --> 31:53.434
I know I'm here,
but I don't feel like it.

31:53.502 --> 31:55.502
Okay, all right, all right.
Why don't you sit down?

31:55.526 --> 31:59.040
Feelings of disassociation this strong
could be a sign of severe PTSD.

31:59.074 --> 32:01.075
No, no, no, no.
Okay. Hey!

32:01.109 --> 32:03.870
I-I just want to talk to Lexi.
I want to -- All right, I'll bring her.

32:03.894 --> 32:06.681
Just -- Tom, just relax.
Okay, sit down, okay?

32:06.715 --> 32:08.716
Okay.
I will bring her.

32:08.750 --> 32:09.950
[ Clears throat ]

32:09.985 --> 32:11.719
I'll go see
if I can find Kadar, huh?

32:11.787 --> 32:13.688
Kadar?
Yeah.

32:13.722 --> 32:16.757
He's far more knowledgeable
about stress disorders.

32:16.792 --> 32:18.926
Kadar is dead, Anne.
You know that.

32:21.630 --> 32:24.231
Lexi doesn't know that.

32:26.101 --> 32:28.102
This is all Lexi.

32:28.136 --> 32:29.570
She's doing this.
Why is she doing this?

32:29.604 --> 32:30.684
What does she want
from me?!

32:30.706 --> 32:32.066
I'm gonna --
I'm gonna go get help.

32:32.100 --> 32:33.420
What does she want from me,
Anne?!

32:33.444 --> 32:34.451
Anne!

32:36.211 --> 32:39.814
[ Panting ]

32:43.118 --> 32:45.086
[ Echoing ] Lexi!

32:51.814 --> 32:53.548
[ Echoing ] Lexi!

32:54.083 --> 32:56.951
[ Wind howling ]

33:04.726 --> 33:06.026
Lexi!

33:11.433 --> 33:13.267
[ Metal scrapes ]

33:17.472 --> 33:20.507
Lexi, wait!

33:20.542 --> 33:23.611
[ Footsteps ]

33:28.316 --> 33:29.583
Dan.

33:29.618 --> 33:30.684
Dan, wait!

33:31.953 --> 33:33.887
[ Panting ]

33:33.922 --> 33:35.923
Where is she?

33:35.991 --> 33:38.592
She won't talk to you.

33:38.627 --> 33:41.895
You're not real.
None of this is real.

33:41.930 --> 33:44.598
This is all part
of a dream.

33:44.633 --> 33:46.266
Lexi,
why are you doing this?!

33:46.301 --> 33:48.669
Bigger question is,
why are you?

33:48.703 --> 33:52.640
It's not like you to give up
on family, Tom.

33:52.674 --> 33:55.809
I want to talk
to Lexi, Dan.

33:55.844 --> 33:57.745
She don't want
to talk to you.

33:57.779 --> 33:59.980
She's too scared.
What's she afraid of?

34:00.015 --> 34:02.816
What'll happen
when you wake up.

34:02.884 --> 34:06.453
What? That the mission will fail?
No.

34:06.521 --> 34:08.589
That it won't.

34:08.623 --> 34:11.257
Why would she be afraid
to succeed? I don't get that.

34:11.292 --> 34:12.931
You don't get it
'cause you're seeing red.

34:12.960 --> 34:14.594
If anybody understands

34:14.629 --> 34:17.563
what you're going through,
Tom, it's me --

34:17.599 --> 34:20.300
to have your daughter
twisted by the Espheni.

34:22.536 --> 34:25.572
But I didn't give up
on mine.

34:25.607 --> 34:28.842
I never gave up on her.

34:28.877 --> 34:31.612
And you can't give up
on yours.

34:31.646 --> 34:33.514
You got to make things
right with her.

34:33.581 --> 34:37.851
Accept her for who she is.

34:37.886 --> 34:41.855
I-I won't accept this.

34:41.889 --> 34:43.690
Wait, wait, wait!

34:46.360 --> 34:47.995
[ Grunts ]

34:48.029 --> 34:49.897
Aah!

34:49.931 --> 34:52.833
You got to get us out of here,
Lexi, now!

34:52.867 --> 34:54.907
[ Echoing ] Do you ever get
tired of barking orders?

34:54.931 --> 34:57.237
Come on. What is this?
What's with all the games?

34:57.272 --> 34:59.406
Do you really need to ask
that question, Dad?

34:59.441 --> 35:01.275
Lexi wants what
all your children want

35:01.342 --> 35:02.943
when we've made
a mistake.

35:02.977 --> 35:05.746
What's that? An escape from reality
or escape from responsibility?

35:05.780 --> 35:07.314
Ben:
You're overthinking it.

35:07.382 --> 35:08.549
How is it that the Espheni

35:08.583 --> 35:09.783
know Lexi better
than her own father?

35:09.818 --> 35:10.918
That's hardly fair, Ben.

35:10.952 --> 35:12.319
Hal: Whoa, whoa, whoa,
whoa, whoa.

35:12.353 --> 35:13.620
Take it easy on him, Ben.

35:13.655 --> 35:15.556
All right?
Cut him a little slack.

35:15.623 --> 35:17.324
Why?
He didn't cut Lexi any.

35:17.358 --> 35:19.493
They messed with her
just like they messed with us --

35:19.527 --> 35:21.328
me with my spikes,
you with those eye bugs,

35:21.362 --> 35:22.496
Matt at the school.

35:22.564 --> 35:24.084
You saved me, dad.
You saved all of us.

35:24.108 --> 35:25.365
But you couldn't
save Lexi.

35:25.400 --> 35:26.867
I was trapped in a prison camp.

35:26.935 --> 35:29.703
She's your own flesh and blood.
She's just like us.

35:29.738 --> 35:31.872
Is she not as important to you?
Of course she is.

35:31.906 --> 35:33.874
I took responsibility
for what you did!

35:33.908 --> 35:35.809
Now you're trying
to blame me for it?!

35:35.844 --> 35:37.311
You weren't there
for her, Dad.

35:37.378 --> 35:38.738
Where were you
when she needed you?

35:38.747 --> 35:40.748
I tried my best
to protect her.

35:40.782 --> 35:42.062
[ Echoing ]
Where were you, Dad?!

35:57.398 --> 36:00.634
[ Echoing ]
You can't keep us here, Lexi!

36:00.668 --> 36:03.704
People are counting on us!

36:07.976 --> 36:09.009
Hello, Tom.

36:12.347 --> 36:15.382
I'm sorry I never got a chance
to say a proper goodbye.

36:15.416 --> 36:17.651
Stop hiding behind
all these faces, Lexi!

36:17.685 --> 36:19.653
Just come out
and show yourself!

36:19.687 --> 36:20.854
She can't.

36:20.889 --> 36:23.457
She's terrified, like I was

36:23.491 --> 36:24.811
when she took away
my last breath.

36:24.835 --> 36:26.727
Lourdes, you know Lexi
better than anyone.

36:26.761 --> 36:29.630
What does she have to be
afraid of?

36:29.664 --> 36:33.534
She doesn't think you'll ever
forgive her for killing me.

36:33.568 --> 36:36.336
She lost you.

36:36.404 --> 36:37.905
She lost Anne.

36:37.939 --> 36:40.707
You'll never forgive her,

36:40.742 --> 36:43.577
never love her,
no matter what she does.

36:44.621 --> 36:47.682
She's lost her whole family.

36:47.683 --> 36:49.751
She's all alone.

36:49.785 --> 36:51.619
There's no coming back.

36:57.693 --> 37:01.696
I understand, Lexi.

37:01.730 --> 37:06.601
I understand
what you want.

37:06.635 --> 37:09.904
This isn't
about the mission.

37:11.707 --> 37:13.942
This is about me...

37:13.976 --> 37:16.911
And Anne and your family.

37:16.979 --> 37:19.714
And these faces --

37:19.748 --> 37:24.052
Weaver and your brothers
and now Lourdes --

37:24.119 --> 37:25.820
you're hiding behind them

37:25.854 --> 37:28.623
because you're terrified that,
no matter what you do,

37:28.691 --> 37:31.526
we'll never forgive you
for what you've done.

37:31.560 --> 37:35.563
Lexi will never be forgiven

37:35.631 --> 37:38.566
because my blood is
on her hands.

37:52.214 --> 37:55.617
How can I ask you
to forgive me

37:55.651 --> 37:58.886
when I can't
even forgive myself?

38:03.361 --> 38:05.529
Tom: I understand
that this isn't a trick,

38:06.376 --> 38:08.510
that this is
just a scared little girl

38:08.578 --> 38:11.580
who's afraid to wake up
and face the cold light of day.

38:11.614 --> 38:13.916
But whatever fears you have,

38:13.950 --> 38:16.919
we need to leave this place
right now.

38:16.986 --> 38:19.388
I don't know
how to reverse this.

38:19.422 --> 38:21.557
I didn't do it on purpose.

38:21.591 --> 38:25.327
I put myself into stasis
with you in the cocoon.

38:27.130 --> 38:29.298
With me?

38:29.332 --> 38:32.101
You're in the cocoon
with me?

38:32.168 --> 38:36.205
So we're dreaming together?

38:36.239 --> 38:39.341
Oh, I should've seen that
from the beginning.

38:39.375 --> 38:40.976
Successful mission,
winning the war --

38:41.010 --> 38:42.970
those are all things
that I've desperately wanted,

38:42.979 --> 38:44.880
things that
I've dreamt about.

38:44.948 --> 38:47.382
[ Indistinct conversation,
laughter ]

38:50.987 --> 38:53.355
What does it mean?

38:54.891 --> 38:57.559
All these people
have made mistakes.

38:57.594 --> 39:00.496
They all have regret.

39:00.530 --> 39:02.498
And yet they
can sit together.

39:02.532 --> 39:04.366
They can break bread
together.

39:07.270 --> 39:09.510
There are so many things I wish
I could go back and undo,

39:09.534 --> 39:11.206
and so many of them
have to do with you.

39:11.274 --> 39:14.076
I'm sorry
that I let you down.

39:14.110 --> 39:16.478
No, my biggest regret
isn't that I trusted you.

39:19.482 --> 39:21.784
It's that
I couldn't forgive you.

39:24.921 --> 39:27.790
This is what we share --
these feelings of regret,

39:27.824 --> 39:31.260
our capacity for guilt
or love or compassion.

39:31.294 --> 39:34.163
These are
all human traits.

39:34.197 --> 39:37.232
And our dream is proof that
you are who you say you are.

39:37.267 --> 39:39.535
You're one of us.
You're not one of them.

39:42.038 --> 39:43.872
It's also proof
that I need to try

39:43.907 --> 39:45.340
to find a way
to forgive you.

39:51.347 --> 39:53.482
But first we need
to wake up.

39:53.516 --> 39:55.017
Are you ready
to do that?

39:55.051 --> 39:56.985
Yes.
Good. Me too.

39:57.020 --> 39:59.154
Maybe if we try together.

40:25.348 --> 40:28.217
I'm searching for the automated
landing protocol.

40:28.251 --> 40:30.285
What's the life-support
situation?

40:30.320 --> 40:33.021
Batteries
over half charge.

40:33.056 --> 40:35.824
So the cocoon
was the right call.

40:35.892 --> 40:37.259
[ Computer beeps ]

40:37.293 --> 40:39.261
There. It's engaged.

40:39.295 --> 40:42.331
We're making our approach.
I can show you.

40:48.938 --> 40:50.339
[ Computer beeps ]

40:53.009 --> 40:56.078
Oh, my god.
We made it.

40:56.112 --> 40:57.179
[ Chuckles ]

40:59.215 --> 41:02.050
I'm the 25th human
to visit the moon.

41:02.085 --> 41:04.519
Which makes me the 26th.

41:12.629 --> 41:14.363
You know that dream --
our dream?

41:14.397 --> 41:15.931
We could make that real.

41:15.965 --> 41:18.967
That could just be
the first.

41:19.035 --> 41:20.369
First of what?

41:20.403 --> 41:23.505
Conversations between father
and daughter.

41:25.341 --> 41:27.876
It's time
I got to know mine.

41:30.446 --> 41:32.247
We're gonna make it, Dad.

41:32.282 --> 41:34.249
I can feel it.

41:49.265 --> 41:50.966
[ Electricity crackling ]

